{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18161"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18161"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"227"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old female presents to her General Practitioner with pain and stiffness in her left shoulder. The pain is described as a dull ache. It has been worsening over the past 6 months with decreased range of motion. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate adjunct therapy for adhesive capsulitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laser therapy","Corticosteroid injection","Oral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","Surgical intervention","Acupuncture"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with adhesive capsulitis, commonly known as frozen shoulder. The condition is characterised by stiffness and pain in the shoulder joint, leading to a significant reduction in range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate adjunct therapy for adhesive capsulitis. It can provide short-term pain relief and improve shoulder function, particularly in the early stages of the condition. The injection helps reduce inflammation and can facilitate participation in physiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser therapy\u003C/strong\u003E has not been shown to be effective for adhesive capsulitis. While it may have some benefit in other shoulder conditions, such as rotator cuff tendinitis, it is not recommended for frozen shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/strong\u003E can help manage pain but are not as effective as corticosteroid injections in improving range of motion in adhesive capsulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for cases that do not respond to conservative management, including physiotherapy and corticosteroid injections. It is not the first-line adjunct therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcupuncture\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some pain relief for musculoskeletal conditions, but there is limited evidence supporting its use as an effective treatment for adhesive capsulitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adhesive capsulitis, also known as frozen shoulder, is characterised by stiffness and pain in the shoulder joint.","Physiotherapy is a key component in the management of adhesive capsulitis, focusing on improving range of motion.","Corticosteroid injections can provide short-term pain relief and improve function in adhesive capsulitis."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18161"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:44:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:45:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"create